item.title: End of Summer, Beginning of Memories
item.dc:creator: jameyprickett
item.description: For most Americans, Labor Day Weekend serves as a symbolic reminder that summer has come to an end. My wife informed me a few years ago that for those who buy into high society, Labor Day is the last day you can wear white. But more importantly, Labor Day weekend is the start of football [...]
item.content:encoded:
For most Americans, Labor Day Weekend serves as a symbolic reminder that summer has come to an end. My wife informed me a few years ago that for those who buy into high society, Labor Day is the last day you can wear white. But more importantly, Labor Day weekend is the start of football season.

Summer is that time of year when our hearts are as free as our toes. Your skin is kissed by the sun and seeing the person you love dressed in sunsets. A great summer day is when the sun is shining and the lawn mower is broken. September is here and summer is gone but the memories we have made will last forever.

This past summer has been filled with family, friends, and good times. I feel blessed that I was able to spend this summer with cousins on the beach, brothers on the lake, and parents at campsites. It was a time for me to slow down and catch my breath. I live a busy life. I am always moving sometimes not even clear on the direction. My mind is always turning. But this summer I was reminded about simple things that are also the most important things. This summer taught me to appreciate the things you have before time makes you appreciate the thing you had. 

What lessons did you learn this summer?

item.title: Project: 50 Movies I Need to See by the End of the Year
item.dc:creator: Eric
item.description: I have enjoyed watching movies my whole life, but it wasn’t until a few years ago that I had fallen in love with them. As a casual fan for so many years, I missed out on a lot of great movies. I have done an admirable job catching up on many of them over the [...]
item.content:encoded:
I have enjoyed watching movies my whole life, but it wasn’t until a few years ago that I had fallen in love with them. As a casual fan for so many years, I missed out on a lot of great movies. I have done an admirable job catching up on many of them over the last couple years, but I am still lacking in many areas. My biggest weakness is in the area of classics, particularly foreign classics. Outside of a handful of Kurosawa films, I haven’t seen too many older foreign titles. I am also still a novice to Film Noir, although I have greatly enjoyed every one I have seen.

In order to continue to push myself to see more great movies, I have compiled this list of 50 movies I must see before the end of the year. Fifty seems like a low number — and it probably is — but I thought it would be a fair amount to squeeze in amidst the summer madness, and there is no telling how busy I will be in the future. These are 50 movies from all eras, and I made sure to include some genres and directors that I want to familiarize myself with. Some are more important than others, but these are all films that I have heard quite a bit about and therefore would like to indulge in them.

With the help of friends and online folk alike, I cut a significantly longer list down to these 50 selections. This will be an ongoing project with my ultimate deadline being to have seen all of these by the end of the year.

The Final List:

City Lights [1931, Chaplin]
Mr. Smith Goes to Washington [1939, Capra]
The Maltese Falcon [1941, Huston]
Casablanca [1942, Curtiz]
Double Indemnity [1944, Wilder]
Rome, Open City [1945, Rossellini]
The Big Sleep [1946, Hawks]
It’s a Wonderful Life [1946, Capra]
Bicycle Thieves [1948, De Sica]
The Asphalt Jungle [1950, Huston]
Sunset Blvd. [1950, Wilder]
Tokyo Story [1953, Ozu]
The Night of the Hunter [1955, Laughton]
The Seventh Seal [1957, Bergman]
Wild Strawberries [1957, Bergman]
Vertigo [1958, Hitchcock]
The 400 Blows [1959, Truffaut]
Breathless [1960, Godard]
The Magnificent Seven [1960, Sturges]
Psycho [1960, Hitchcock]
The Hustler [1961, Rossen]
8 1/2 [1963, Fellini]
Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb [1964, Kubrick]
Cool Hand Luke [1967, Rosenberg]
The Graduate [1967, Nichols]
Night of the Living Dead [1968, Romero]
Once Upon a Time in the West [1968, Leone]
Last Tango in Paris [1972, Bertolucci]
The Exorcist [1973, Friedkin]
The Godfather: Part II [1974, Coppola]
Jaws [1975, Spielberg]
Annie Hall [1977, Allen]
Airplane! [1980, Abrahams & Zucker]
Blade Runner [1982, Scott]
Back to the Future [1985, Zemeckis]
Akira [1988, Ohtomo]
Grave of the Fireflies [1988, Takahata]
Army of Darkness [1992, Raimi]
Unforgiven [1992, Eastwood]
Schindler’s List [1993, Spielberg]
L.A. Confidential [1997, Hanson]
Dark City [1998, Proyas]
The Thin Red Line [1998, Malick]
Dancer in the Dark [2000, von Trier]
Mulholland Drive [2001, Lynch]
Hotel Rwanda [2004, George]
Million Dollar Baby [2004, Eastwood]
Crash [2005, Haggis]
The Prestige [2006, Nolan]
Zodiac [2007, Fincher]

Any thoughts? Comments? Concerns? While I likely won’t make any more changes to the list, I am always looking for new suggestions all the same.

item.title: Bukhansan Ridge Climb
item.dc:creator: skunkabilly
item.description: When folks think of what to do in Korea, rock climbing isn’t really the first thing that comes to mind, but I would argue it is the best way to see Korea. The palaces and markets are cool and all, but if you live in a big city, wandering around another big city gets old [...]
item.content:encoded:
When folks think of what to do in Korea, rock climbing isn’t really the first thing that comes to mind,

but I would argue it is the best way to see Korea.

The palaces and markets are cool and all,

but if you live in a big city, wandering around another big city gets old fast.

Bukhansan National Park is at the edge of the big city, accessible by public transport, with lots of English signage.

So if you were to go there to hike, especially on a weekend, the trail would be buku crowded.

Not so if you climb.

We did a ridge climb with lots of being roped up but scrambling and not always doing technical climbing,

there were enough tricky spots to keep it challenging…of course it helped I’m not the best climber in the world.

The best part? Clear skies, a rare event that lets one see beyond the Han river.

And there was no one else on the route to have to share with.

Korea, just the way I like it.

So hopefully I’ll be able to catch up with that stuff in the next few weeks but in the mean time here’s some shots from a football game I shot last week in Reedsville for the Messenger. The best part about shooting football in the beginning of the season (aside from just the fact that football’s back) is that usually for the first drive or two you get just unbelievable light. Then for the rest of the season it’s complete crap so you gotta make the most of it while it’s there. So here’s some shots from the first game of the 2011 football season.
